post_text:
It is not too late to apply for Pandemic-EBT. Most families who qualify for free and reduced lunch or who are on Medi-Cal will automatically receive their P-EBT card in the mail. Due to COVID-19 and household income changes, you
may apply or reapply for AUSD Nutrition Services free and reduced-price meals, which could qualify you to receive P-EBT benefits.

We encourage you to take advantage of these useful resources by following the steps below.
1. Families with children who are eligible for free and reduced-price meals and who do not
get their P-EBT card in the mail by May 22, 2020, must apply online before Ju;y 15, 2020, at ca.p-ebt.org/
2. If you have had a household income change or have not previously filled out a free and reduced-price meal application, you may do so here https://azusa.rocketscanapps.com. Once the application is filled out and eligibility is confirmed, you can apply for PEBT

post_text:
March 20, 2020

Dear AUSD Community,

This afternoon, Dr. Debra Duardo, Superintendent of the Los Angeles County Office of Education (LACOE), announced the recommendation that schools remain closed until Tuesday, May 5, 2020. This recommendation was made in consideration of the Los Angeles County ‚ÄúSafer at Home‚Äù and the Governor‚Äôs ‚ÄúStay-at Home‚Äù orders. Based on this recommendation from LACOE, schools in the Azusa Unified School District will remain closed until Tuesday, May 5, 2020.

The health and safety of our community is our utmost priority. We, along with the Los Angeles County Office of Education (LACOE), have been closely monitoring the development of COVID-19. We understand that this extension will raise a lot of questions. We will continue to provide updates as we move into the next steps of planning and implementation for extended school closure. This continues to be a rapidly evolving situation. We are thankful for your patience and understanding as we navigate this together.

March 20, 2020

Dear AUSD Community,

This afternoon, Dr. Debra Duardo, Superintendent of the Los Angeles County Office of Education (LACOE), announced the recommendation that schools remain closed until Tuesday, May 5, 2020. This recommendation was made in consideration of the Los Angeles County ‚ÄúSafer at Home‚Äù and the Governor‚Äôs ‚ÄúStay-at Home‚Äù orders. Based on this recommendation from LACOE, schools in the Azusa Unified School District will remain closed until Tuesday, May 5, 2020.

The health and safety of our community is our utmost priority. We, along with the Los Angeles County Office of Education (LACOE), have been closely monitoring the development of COVID-19. We understand that this extension will raise a lot of questions. We will continue to provide updates as we move into the next steps of planning and implementation for extended school closure. This continues to be a rapidly evolving situation. We are thankful for your patience and understanding as we navigate this together.
